Decisions Made
- Added shell-based regression harnesses for skill orchestration contracts instead of introducing a Python-only test dependency.
- Added fixture-driven structure tests for batch-refine and curate-report so deterministic changeset/report behavior is validated separately from prompt-contract checks.
- Added a dedicated GitHub Actions workflow to run all local regression harnesses on pull requests and pushes to main.

Problems Encountered
- The working workspace already contained unrelated modifications on a non-main branch, so a separate worktree from origin/main was used to isolate this PR.
- The CLI `curate` command reads operator input from an interactive loop, which made full non-interactive action execution brittle in automation.
- A couple of assertions were initially too literal and had to be relaxed to match stable CLI behavior rather than exact formatting details.

Constraints Identified
- Tests should remain shell/jq-based to align with the repository's current tooling and avoid adding a new Python test dependency.
- PR content must exclude unrelated uncommitted workspace changes.
- Interactive CLI flows can only be smoke-tested unless the command grows a non-interactive mode.

Open Questions
- Whether `mark-evidence` should get the same structure-test treatment as batch-refine and curate-report.
- Whether the `curate` command should gain a non-interactive mode for deeper automated testing.
- Whether README or adoption docs should explicitly mention the new regression harness workflow.

Context
- Implemented a full regression test stack covering knowledge-gate CLI commands, orchestration contract fixtures for batch-refine and curate-report, deterministic structure tests for their changeset/report outputs, and CI execution via tests/all.sh and .github/workflows/test-harness.yml.
